The Los Angeles Regional Water Quality Control Board (LARWQCB) will hold a public hearing to consider adoption of a resolution to approve an amendment to the Water Quality Control Plan for the Los Angeles Region (Basin Plan) to incorporate a Total Maximum Daily Load (TMDL) for bacteria in the Los Angeles River Watershed.

The proposed Basin Plan amendment will establish TMDLs for bacteria in the Los Angeles River Watershed to protect water contact recreation (REC-1) beneficial uses in the Los Angeles River and its tributaries. The proposed TMDLs include numeric targets, source analysis, allocations, and a compliance schedule. The proposed TMDLs also include an implementation plan that identifies the actions necessary to achieve the numeric targets and allocations, and a monitoring plan to measure progress toward attaining water quality standards and TMDL numeric targets.

The proposed Basin Plan amendment and the supporting documents are available at the LARWQCB website at: http://www.waterboards.ca.gov/losangeles/water_issues/programs/tmdl/la_river_bacteria.shtml

The public comment period for this item will close at 12:00 P.M. on February 10, 2017. Written comments must be received by the LARWQCB by that time at the following address:

320 West 4th Street, Suite 200

Los Angeles, CA 90013

Attention: Annelisa Moe

Comments may be submitted by e-mail. File size should not exceed 15 megabytes. If submitting comments by e-mail, please indicate in the subject line, “COMMENT LETTER – LA River Bacteria TMDL.” Electronic files should be submitted in Adobe Portable Document Format (PDF) to:

commentletters@waterboards.ca.gov

If you have questions about the proposed Basin Plan amendment, please contact Annelisa Moe at (213) 576-6782 or by e-mail at Annelisa.Moe@Waterboards.CA.Gov.

The public hearing will be held at the LARWQCB office located at 320 West 4th Street, Suite 200, Los Angeles, CA 90013.

The LARWQCB’s agenda is available on the Internet at: http://www.waterboards.ca.gov/losangeles/board_info/agenda/index.shtml

You may view the LARWQCB’s procedure for the hearing at: http://www.waterboards.ca.gov/losangeles/board_info/agenda/2017/2017_board_hearings.shtml

If you have any questions about the hearing procedures, you may contact the Clerk to the Board at (213) 576-6615.

The LARWQCB requests that this notice be brought to the attention of persons who you know will be interested in this matter.

The LARWQCB is committed to full compliance with the Americans with Disabilities Act, and the Fair Employment and Housing Act. If you require special accommodations, please contact the Clerk to the Board at (213) 576-6615, at least five (5) days prior to the scheduled meeting.

The LARWQCB appreciates your cooperation in this important matter.

Sincerely,

The most common cause of PID is a sexually transmitted infection (STI), such as chlamydia or gonorrhea. Other causes include bacterial infections, such as bacterial vaginosis, and infections that occur after childbirth, abortion, or other gynecological procedures.

PID can cause a variety of symptoms, including pelvic pain, fever, abnormal vaginal discharge, pain during sex, and pain during urination. If left untreated, PID can lead to serious complications, such as infertility, ectopic pregnancy, and chronic pelvic pain.

Treatment for PID typically involves antibiotics to clear the infection. In some cases, surgery may be necessary to remove infected tissue or to repair damage caused by the infection. It is important to seek medical attention if you experience symptoms of PID, as early treatment can help prevent complications.

In addition to medical treatment, there are several things you can do to help prevent PID. These include practicing safe sex, getting regular STI screenings, and avoiding douching, which can disrupt the natural balance of bacteria in the vagina and increase the risk of infection.

Overall, PID is a serious condition that can have long-term effects on a woman’s health. By taking steps to prevent infection and seeking prompt treatment if symptoms occur, you can help protect yourself from this condition.

Healing can take many forms, from the physical healing of a wound to the emotional healing of a broken heart. It can be a slow and gradual process, or it can happen quickly and dramatically. But no matter how it happens, healing is always a sign that our bodies are working to restore balance and health.

There are many things we can do to support our bodies’ natural healing processes. Eating a healthy diet, getting regular exercise, and getting enough sleep are all important. But there are also many other things we can do, such as practicing relaxation techniques, spending time in nature, and connecting with others.

Ultimately, health is about more than just the absence of disease. It’s about feeling good in our bodies and our minds, and being able to live our lives to the fullest. When we are healthy, we are better able to cope with the challenges of life and to enjoy the good times. So let’s all strive to be as healthy as we can be, in every sense of the word.
